rk?\",{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"className\":\"font-medium text-foreground\",\"children\":\"How does the temperature slider work?\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Switch to Temperature mode and drag the slider from 0 K (absolute zero) to 6000 K. Each element's cell changes color to show whether it is solid (blue), liquid (green), or gas (orange) at that temperature, based on its melting and boiling points.\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",\"What formulas does the molar mass calculator support?\",{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"className\":\"font-medium text-foreground\",\"children\":\"What formulas does the molar mass calculator support?\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"The calculator handles simple formulas (H2O, NaCl), parentheses (Ca(OH)2), brackets ([Cu(NH3)4]SO4), nested groups (Mg3(PO4)2), hydrate notation (CuSO4·5H2O), and Unicode subscript digits.\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",\"Can I export the periodic table data?\",{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"className\":\"font-medium text-foreground\",\"children\":\"Can I export the periodic table data?\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Yes. Click the Export button to download element data as CSV (for spreadsheets), JSON (for developers), PDF (print-ready table with all selected properties), or PNG (screenshot of the current table view). You can choose which properties to include.\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",\"Does the electron configuration builder follow the Aufbau principle?\",{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"className\":\"font-medium text-foreground\",\"children\":\"Does the electron configuration builder follow the Aufbau principle?\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Yes. The builder fills orbitals in the standard Aufbau order (1s → 2s → 2p → 3s → ...) and displays electrons following Hund's rule (maximum spin multiplicity). You can also click individual orbital boxes to create custom configurations.\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",\"Does the tool work on mobile?\",{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"className\":\"font-medium text-foreground\",\"children\":\"Does the tool work on mobile?\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"The periodic table is optimized for desktop viewports (1024px+) where you can see the full 18-column layout. It is usable on tablets in landscape mode. On phones, horizontal scrolling is available but the experience is best on larger screens.\"}]]}],\"$L46\",\"$L47\",\"$L48\"]}]]}]\n3c:[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h3\",null,{\"className\":\"text-sm font-semibold\",\"children\":\"Confusing atomic number with atomic mass\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Atomic number = proton count (unique to each element); atomic mass = average mass of isotopes (varies by sample). The table shows both — read the right one for your problem.\"}]]}]\n3d:[\"$\",\"li\",\"Reading electron configuration left-to-right\",{\"className\":\"flex gap-3 rounded-lg border border-border bg-card p-4\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{\"ref\":\"$undefined\",\"iconNode\":\"$37:1:props:children:1:props:children:0:props:children:0:props:iconNode\",\"className\":\"lucide-triangle-alert mt-0.5 size-5 shrink-0 text-pink-500\"}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h3\",null,{\"className\":\"text-sm font-semibold\",\"children\":\"Reading electron configuration left-to-right\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Electron configurations follow the Aufbau order (1s → 2s → 2p → 3s → 3p → 4s → 3d…), not strict atomic-number order. The viewer shows the proper filling order so you don't have to memorize the diagram.\"}]]}]]}]\n3e:[\"$\",\"li\",\"Skipping isotope notation\",{\"className\":\"flex gap-3 rounded-lg border border-border bg-card p-4\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{\"ref\":\"$undefined\",\"iconNode\":\"$37:1:props:children:1:props:children:0:props:children:0:props:iconNode\",\"className\":\"lucide-triangle-alert mt-0.5 size-5 shrink-0 text-pink-500\"}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h3\",null,{\"className\":\"text-sm font-semibold\",\"children\":\"Skipping isotope notation\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"When a problem specifies an isotope (¹⁴C, ²³⁵U), the atomic mass on the table is the average — not what the problem is asking for. Use the listed isotope mass instead.\"}]]}]]}]\n3f:[\"$\",\"section\",null,{\"aria-labelledby\":\"tool-insights-takeaways\",\"className\":\"rounded-lg border border-brand/30 bg-brand/5 p-5\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"id\":\"tool-insights-takeaways\",\"className\":\"text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight\",\"children\":\"Key Takeaways\"}],[\"$\",\"ul\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-3 space-y-2\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"li\",\"The Interactive Periodic Table covers all 118 elements with temperature phase, heatmaps, and electron configurations.\",{\"className\":\"flex items-start gap-2\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{\"ref\":\"$undefined\",\"iconNode\":[[\"circle\",{\"cx\":\"12\",\"cy\":\"12\",\"r\":\"10\",\"key\":\"1mglay\"}],[\"path\",{\"d\":\"m9 12 2 2 4-4\",\"key\":\"dzmm74\"}]],\"className\":\"lucide-circle-check mt-0.5 size-4 shrink-0 text-brand\"}],[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"text-sm text-foreground\",\"children\":\"The Interactive Periodic Table covers all 118 elements with temperature phase, heatmaps, and electron configurations.\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"li\",\"It includes a molar mass calculator that parses chemical formulas with parentheses and hydrates.\",{\"className\":\"flex items-start gap-2\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L5\",null,{\"ref\":\"$undefine